# Generation Clock: term/epoch numbers across leader changes
direction: down

T1: "TERM 1\nLeader: A\n(initial)" {
  style: { fill: "#c8e6c9"; stroke: "#1b5e20"; stroke-width: 2; border-radius: 8 }
  L1: "Leader A\nappends entries\n[1,1,SETx=1]\n[2,1,SETy=2]"
}

Crash1: "Node A crashes (or network partition)\nFollowers detect via heartbeat timeout" {
  shape: rectangle
  style: { fill: "#ffcdd2"; stroke: "#b71c1c"; border-radius: 8 }
}

T2: "TERM 2\nLeader: B\n(elected by majority)" {
  style: { fill: "#bbdefb"; stroke: "#0d47a1"; stroke-width: 2; border-radius: 8 }
  L2: "Leader B\nincrements term to 2\nrequests votes\nwins majority\nappends [3,2,DEL x]"
}

Note1: "Network partition heals \u2014 A comes back thinking it's still leader of term 1\nWhat happens? \u2192" {
  shape: rectangle
  style: { fill: "#fff4c2"; stroke: "#bf360c"; border-radius: 8 }
}

Reject: "OLD-TERM REJECTION\nA tries to AppendEntries(term=1)\nFollowers reply 'I'm at term 2, reject'\nA learns of higher term \u2192 demotes itself to Follower\n\nGeneration clock = the safety mechanism\nthat keeps split-brain from causing data loss." {
  shape: rectangle
  style: { fill: "#e1bee7"; stroke: "#4a148c"; stroke-width: 2; border-radius: 8 }
}

T1 -> Crash1
Crash1 -> T2
T2 -> Note1
Note1 -> Reject
